ity should mean and how it could be deployed. How Reason Almost Lost Its Mind brings to life the people—Herbert Simon, Oskar Morgenstern, Herman Kahn, Anatol Rapoport, Thomas Schelling, and many others—and places, including the RAND Corporation, the Center for Advanced Study in the Behavioral Sciences, the Cowles Commission for Research and Economics, and the Council on Foreign Relations, that played a key role in putting forth a “Cold War rationality.” Decision makers harnessed this picture of rationality—optimizing, formal, algorithmic, and mechanical—in their quest to understand phenomena as diverse as economic transactions, biological evolution, political elections, international relations, and military strategy. The authors chronicle and illuminate what it meant to be rational in the age of nuclear brinkmanship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCold WarxPhilosophy. 0aCold War. 0aGame theoryxPolitical aspects. 0aRationalismxPolitical aspects. 0aReasonxPolitical aspects. 0aWorld politicsy1945-1989. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aDaston, Lorraine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aGordin, Michael D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKlein, Judy L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSturm, Thomas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226046778423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226046778.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles